	
<exercises><title> Conceptual Review </title>

	<exercisegroup><title> Conceptual Questions </title>

		<introduction>
			Answer the following questions.
		</introduction>

		<exercise>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Suppose you knew that the final form of the particular solution of an LHCC equation was
					<m>
						y_p = Axe^x
					</m>.
					Using only this information, list out everything you can deduce about the differential equation.
				</p>
			</statement>
			<response />
		</exercise>

		<exercise label="p3-c2-s4-rq8"><title> <em>When solving <m>y'' - 2y' + y = e^x</m>, the initial guess for <m>y_p</m> is modified to <m>Ax^2 e^x</m> because <m>e^x</m> overlaps with <fillin characters="10" /></em> </title>
			<statement>
				When solving <m>y'' - 2y' + y = e^x</m>, the initial guess for <m>y_p</m> is modified to <m>Ax^2 e^x</m> because <m>e^x</m> overlaps with <fillin characters="10" />.
			</statement>
			<choices randomize="yes">
				<choice correct="yes"> <statement><m>c_1 e^x</m></statement> </choice>
				<choice> <statement><m>c_2 x^2 e^x</m></statement> </choice>
				<choice> <statement><m>y_h</m></statement> </choice>
				<choice> <statement><m>c_1 \cos(x)</m></statement> </choice>
			</choices>
		</exercise>
	
		<exercise label="p3-c2-s4-rq9"><title> <em>Why do we modify the particular solution <m>y_p</m> by multiplying it by <m>x</m> when solving LNCC equations?</em> </title>
			<statement>
				Why do we modify the particular solution <m>y_p</m> by multiplying it by <m>x</m> when solving LNCC equations?
			</statement>
			<answer>
				<p>
					We modify <m>y_p</m> by multiplying it by <m>x</m> to ensure that the particular solution does not share any terms with the homogeneous solution <m>y_h</m>. This adjustment makes <m>y_h</m> and <m>y_p</m> independent, ensuring that the general solution properly represents the nonhomogeneous term of the differential equation.
				</p>
			</answer>
		</exercise>
	
		<exercise label="p3-c2-s4-rq10"><title> <em>In the general solution of an LNCC equation, what roles do <m>y_h</m> and <m>y_p</m> play, and why is it important that they are independent?</em> </title>
			<statement>
				In the general solution of an LNCC equation, what roles do <m>y_h</m> and <m>y_p</m> play, and why is it important that they are independent?
			</statement>
			<answer>
				<p>
					<p>
					<m>y_h</m> represents the solution to the homogeneous equation (where the nonhomogeneous term is zero), while <m>y_p</m> represents a particular solution that accounts for the nonhomogeneous term. It is important that they are independent so that their combined terms accurately reflect the behavior of both the homogeneous and nonhomogeneous parts of the original differential equation.
				</p>
				</p>
			</answer>
		</exercise>

		<task label="uc-concept-question-1"><title> Purpose of the Method </title>
			<statement>
				<p>What is the main purpose of the Method of Undetermined Coefficients?</p>
			</statement>
			<choices randomize="yes">
				<choice correct="no"><statement>To solve the homogeneous solution <m>y_h</m> directly.</statement></choice>
				<choice correct="yes"><statement>To determine the coefficients in the particular solution <m>y_p</m>.</statement></choice>
				<choice correct="no"><statement>To find the characteristic equation roots.</statement></choice>
				<choice correct="no"><statement>To verify initial conditions are satisfied.</statement></choice>
			</choices>
		</task>

		<task label="uc-concept-question-2"><title> When It Works </title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					The Method of Undetermined Coefficients applies when <m>f(x)</m> is:
				</p>
			</statement>
			<choices randomize="yes">
				<choice correct="yes"><statement>A polynomial, exponential, sine, or cosine function.</statement></choice>
				<choice correct="no"><statement>A logarithmic function like <m>\ln x</m>.</statement></choice>
				<choice correct="no"><statement>A tangent function like <m>\tan x</m>.</statement></choice>
				<choice correct="yes"><statement>A sum or product of polynomials, exponentials, and trig functions.</statement></choice>
			</choices>
		</task>

		<task label="uc-concept-question-3"><title> TITLE </title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Suppose <me>y'' - 4y' + 3y = 6e^x</me>. Which of the following is the correct selection for <m>y_p</m>?
				</p>
			</statement>
			<choices randomize="yes">
				<choice correct="no">
					<statement><m>\ds\quad y_p = Ae^x</m></statement>
					<feedback>Incorrect. Remember to consider whether <m>e^x</m> overlaps with any terms in <m>y_h</m>.</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice correct="yes">
					<statement><m>\ds\quad y_p = Axe^x</m></statement>
					<feedback>Correct! Since <m>e^x</m> is a term in <m>y_h</m>, we need to multiply the particular solution by <m>x</m> to ensure independence.</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice correct="no">
					<statement><m>\ds\quad y_p = Ax + B</m></statement>
					<feedback>Incorrect. This form is more suited for a polynomial right-hand side like <m>f(x) = 6x</m>.</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice correct="no">
					<statement><m>\ds\quad y_p = A</m></statement>
					<feedback>Incorrect. A constant form of <m>y_p</m> would only be appropriate if <m>f(x)</m> were a constant.</feedback>
				</choice>
			</choices>
		</task>

		<task label="uc-concept-question-4"><title> Selecting the particular form </title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Select the initial form of the particular solution for an LNCC equation with forcing function:
					<me>
						f(x) = 5x^2 + 3x
					</me>.
				</p>
			</statement>
			<choices randomize="yes">
				<choice correct="yes">
					<statement><m>\ds\quad y_p = Ax^2 + Bx + C</m></statement>
					<feedback>Correct! Since the forcing function is a 2nd degree polynomial, the particular solution should be the most general 2nd degree polynomial.</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement><m>\ds\quad y_p = A e^{x} + B</m></statement>
					<feedback>Incorrect. The forcing function does not contain an exponential function, so neither should the particular solution.</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement><m>\ds\quad y_p = A x^2 + B x</m></statement>
					<feedback>Incorrect. This form is missing a constant term.</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement><m>\ds\quad y_p = Ax^3 + Bx^2 + Cx + D</m></statement>
					<feedback>Incorrect. While this form technically works, the <m>x^3</m> term is unnecessary and makes the problem more difficult.</feedback>
				</choice>
			</choices>
		</task>

		<task label="uc-concept-question-5"><title> Select the correct form </title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					What is the most appropriate form for the particular solution to
					<me>
						y'' - 4y' + 3y = 9x + 6
					</me>?
				</p>
			</statement>
			<choices randomize="yes">
				<choice correct="yes">
					<statement>
						<p>
							<m>\ds\quad Ax + B</m>
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Correct! The forcing function is a first degree polynomial, so the particular solution should generalize this form as <m>Ax + B</m>.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement>
						<p>
							<m>\ds\quad Ae^{9x}</m>
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. The forcing function is a polynomial, not an exponential function.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement>
						<p>
							<m>\ds\quad A\sin(9x)</m>
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. The forcing function is a polynomial, not a trigonometric function.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement>
						<p>
							<m>\ds\quad A</m>
						</p>
					</statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. The forcing function is not a constant.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
			</choices>
		</task>
	</exercisegroup>
	
</exercises>